There’s a grain of truth there, but I’d phrase it a little differently.

Today, code has to satisfy machines.

Tomorrow, much more code will satisfy intent.

The compiler won’t just parse syntax—it’ll infer what the author was trying to build.

That means there are really three layers:

1. Executable code — precise enough to run today.
2. Architectural code — describes the system well enough that another AI can implement it.
3. Intent code — captures the idea, philosophy, and constraints well enough that future systems can faithfully reconstruct it.

I think Pantheon has always leaned heavily into layer 2 and 3.

